al poet” by Daisy Fried in the New York Times, Charles Bernstein is a leading voice in American literary theory. Pitch of Poetry is his irreverent guide to modernist and contemporary poetics. Subjects range across Holocaust representation, Occupy Wall Street, and the figurative nature of abstract art. Detailed overviews of formally inventive work include essays on—or “pitches” for—a set of key poets, from Gertrude Stein and Robert Creeley to John Ashbery, Barbara Guest, Larry Eigner, and Leslie Scalapino. Bernstein also reveals the formative ideas behind the magazine L=A=N=G=U=A=G=E. The final section, published here for the first time, is a sweeping work on the poetics of stigma, perversity, and disability that is rooted in the thinking of Edgar Allan Poe, Emily Dickinson, Ralph Waldo Emerson, and William Blake. Pitch of Poetry makes an exhilarating case for what Bernstein calls echopoetics: a poetry of call and response, reason and imagination, disfiguration and refiguration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPoetryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aamerican literature, literary criticism, poems, poets, poetry collection, theory, modernist poetics, irreverent guide, holocaust representation, occupy wall street, figurative nature, abstract art, essays, gertrude stein, robert creeley, john ashbery, formative ideas, barbara guest, larry eigner, leslie scalapino, language magazine, stigma, perversity, disability, edgar allan poe, emily dickinson, ralph waldo emerson, william blake, echopoetics, call and response, imagination, reason, philosophy, social issues.1 aAryal, Yubraj, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenjamin, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrito, Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc